{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The embedding vector produced for a given query string has the correct dimensionality for the vector database index.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is the handoff between embedding producer and index configuration, not pure local math. The behavior text is about compatibility: \"correct dimensionality for the vector database index.\" A unit test of one function can miss a real mismatch between embedding-client output shape and configured index dimension across modules. Higher levels were considered and rejected: System is disqualified because this specific check can be reproduced with in-process wiring (embedder adapter + index schema validator) without real OS/network/subprocess. Agentic is disqualified because correctness here is vector length, not model judgment quality.","test_description":"Wire query handler -> embedding adapter -> index schema check with a test index config (e.g., dimension 1536). Use controlled embedding responses of matching and mismatching lengths and assert request acceptance/rejection at module boundary.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.28,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The similarity search returns results ordered by descending cosine similarity score.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"The issue states search is \"against a vector database,\" and this behavior asserts actual returned order by cosine score. Real failure often lives in DB metric/index settings or client/DB ordering semantics; mocks/fakes can always return pre-sorted fixtures and hide that defect. Lower-level miss-proof: an integration test with mocked repository can pass even when real DB is configured with wrong distance metric or ascending sort. Higher level rejected: Agentic is disqualified because no AI output-quality judgment is required for this behavior.","test_description":"Run a real vector DB instance, index known vectors, execute search through the real search path, and assert returned scores are strictly non-increasing and IDs match expected cosine ranking.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.3,"System":0.45,"Agentic":0.07,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The LLM re-ranking step changes the order of at least some results compared to the raw similarity ranking when the query has nuanced intent.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Behavior explicitly depends on model judgment: \"LLM re-ranking\" and \"nuanced intent.\" A stubbed reranker can be forced to reorder and will hide whether the real LLM actually makes contextual distinctions. Lower-level miss-proof: integration tests with deterministic fixtures validate plumbing only, not whether the model changes ordering on nuanced queries. Higher level rejected by concrete text: Workflow is disqualified because this behavior targets a single model decision step (re-ranking), not multiple agentic decisions in sequence.","test_description":"Use real LLM reranking on a curated nuanced-query set where raw similarity order is known; assert that in at least a defined fraction of cases, reranked order differs from raw and remains valid output format.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.06,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.78,"Workflow":0.06}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A query with no close matches in the database returns an empty result set rather than low-relevance noise.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"This outcome depends on real embedding/model behavior plus retrieval thresholding for \"no close matches.\" With mocked embeddings/scores, tests can trivially pass and miss real false-positive noise caused by actual model-space geometry. Lower-level miss-proof: integration tests with fixed vectors do not expose semantic drift where unrelated queries still map near corpus vectors. Higher level rejected by text: Workflow is disqualified because the empty-result decision can be validated at retrieval/noise-filter boundary and does not require multiple sequential model decisions.","test_description":"Populate corpus with a coherent domain, run real embedding+search on out-of-domain queries, and assert empty results (or below strict relevance threshold) across repeated runs/cases to catch noise leakage.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.09,"System":0.22,"Agentic":0.6,"Workflow":0.06}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The end-to-end latency from receiving the query to returning re-ranked results stays below 2 seconds for the median case.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"The measured path is explicitly end-to-end: \"from receiving the query to returning re-ranked results.\" In this issue, that path includes multiple agentic steps in sequence (embedding model call, then LLM rerank). Real failure is cumulative pipeline latency; mocking one or both model calls hides queueing/compounding effects and median breaches. Lower-level miss-proof: a single-step or mocked-latency test can pass while true two-model pipeline median exceeds 2s. Higher level not applicable beyond Workflow in the provided taxonomy.","test_description":"Run production-like end-to-end load on the real pipeline (embedding + vector search + LLM rerank), collect latency distribution over sufficient sample size, and assert p50 < 2.0s for the full response path.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.2,"Agentic":0.25,"Workflow":0.5}}]}
